Step 2: Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

Plot random images with labels from each category¶

In [17]:
categories = labels['Label'].unique()
fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 4, figsize=(15, 10))
axes = axes.ravel()
for i, category in enumerate(categories):
    sample = labels[labels['Label'] == category].index[0]
    axes[i].imshow(images[sample])
    axes[i].set_title(category)
    axes[i].axis('off')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Step 3: Data Pre-processing¶

Convert BGR images to RGB¶

In [19]:
images = images[..., ::-1]

Resize images for consistenc¶

In [20]:
from tensorflow.image import resize
In [21]:
image_size = (128, 128)
images_resized = np.array([resize(img, image_size).numpy() for img in images])
print("Resized Images Shape:", images_resized.shape)

Resized Images Shape: (4750, 128, 128, 3)

Encode target variable¶

In [22]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
In [23]:
le = LabelEncoder()
labels_encoded = le.fit_transform(labels['Label'])
labels_categorical = to_categorical(labels_encoded)

Normalize image data¶

In [24]:
images_normalized = images_resized / 255.0

Split the data¶

In [25]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    images_normalized, labels_categorical, test_size=0.2, random_state=42
)
print("Train/Test Split:", X_train.shape, X_test.shape)

Train/Test Split: (3800, 128, 128, 3) (950, 128, 128, 3)

Observations:¶

- Images resized to (128, 128, 3) and normalized.¶

- Target variable encoded to categorical format.¶

- Dataset split into training and testing sets.¶

Step 4: Model Building¶

Building a CNN model¶

In [29]:
model = Sequential([
    Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=(128, 128, 3)),
    MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),
    Dropout(0.2),

    Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),
    Dropout(0.3),

    Flatten(),
    Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(0.4),
    Dense(12, activation='softmax')
])
In [31]:
model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

Training the model¶

In [32]:
history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, validation_split=0.2, epochs=10, batch_size=32)

Step 6: Model Performance Improvement¶

Applying Data Augmentation¶

In [37]:
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator
In [38]:
data_gen = ImageDataGenerator(
    rotation_range=30,
    width_shift_range=0.2,
    height_shift_range=0.2,
    shear_range=0.2,
    zoom_range=0.2,
    horizontal_flip=True
)

Train the model with augmented data¶

In [39]:
data_gen.fit(X_train)
model_aug = Sequential([
    Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=(128, 128, 3)),
    MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),
    Dropout(0.2),

    Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),
    Dropout(0.3),

    Flatten(),
    Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(0.4),
    Dense(12, activation='softmax')
])

When using Sequential models, prefer using an `Input(shape)` object as the first layer in the model instead.

In [40]:
model_aug.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
history_aug = model_aug.fit(
    data_gen.flow(X_train, y_train, batch_size=32),
    validation_data=(X_test, y_test),
    epochs=10
)
